    </div>

    <p>It is distinct from content SEO and link building, though deeply intertwined with both. You can write brilliant copy and earn formidable backlinks, but if Googlebot cannot crawl a site efficiently or pages take five seconds to render, those efforts yield diminished returns, like pouring water into a bucket riddled with holes. Technical SEO is the foundation layer upon which every other form of optimisation rests.</p>

    <p>Google processes trillions of pages and allocates a finite crawl budget to each domain, a resource as scarce and as valuable as shelf space in a prime retailer. Sites with clean architecture, fast responses, and unambiguous signals earn more frequent crawls and more complete indexation, while sites burdened by bloated code, broken links, and contradictory directives find themselves partially indexed at best, invisible at worst.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Why Guildford Businesses Need Technical SEO</h2>

    <p>Guildford is not a typical market town. <strong>Surrey Research Park</strong> houses technology companies including satellite manufacturer <strong>SSTL</strong> and defence technology firms that spun out of <strong>BAE Systems</strong>. The <strong>University of Surrey</strong> produces a steady pipeline of technology startups, and gaming studios like <strong>Media Molecule</strong> and <strong>Hello Games</strong> have established their headquarters here. These organisations operate complex websites that demand technical precision.</p>

    <p>This commercial landscape creates specific technical SEO challenges, each one a puzzle that rewards analytical thinking over brute-force fixes:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Technology companies on Surrey Research Park</strong> often run JavaScript-heavy web applications that search engines struggle to render. React, Angular, and Vue frontends require server-side rendering or pre-rendering strategies to ensure Google can index content reliably.</li>
      <li><strong>Property agencies</strong> serving Guildford's market, where average property prices exceed £600,000, manage thousands of listing pages that create crawl budget pressure, duplicate content issues, and index bloat from expired listings.</li>
      <li><strong>Professional services firms</strong> along Guildford High Street compete for high-value local searches where page speed and mobile performance directly affect conversion rates.</li>
      <li><strong>Gaming studios</strong> publish media-rich sites with large image and video assets that compromise page speed scores without considered optimisation.</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare providers</strong> near <strong>Royal Surrey Hospital</strong> must maintain YMYL compliance where technical trust signals carry additional weight in rankings.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>In every one of these cases, the technical layer is not optional: it is the boundary line between visibility and obscurity in a market that does not forgive complacency.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Core Web Vitals and Site Speed</h2>

    <p>Core Web Vitals are Google's measurable performance metrics that directly influence rankings, assessing three aspects of user experience: loading performance, interactivity, and visual stability.</p>

    <h3>Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)</h3>

    <p>LCP measures how quickly the largest visible element loads, with Google requiring LCP under 2.5 seconds. Most underperforming sites I audit in Guildford fail this metric because of unoptimised hero images, render-blocking CSS, or slow server response from shared hosting environments.</p>

    <p>I address LCP by implementing responsive image formats (WebP and AVIF with appropriate fallbacks), preloading critical assets, eliminating render-blocking resources, and upgrading hosting infrastructure where necessary.</p>

    <h3>Interaction to Next Paint (INP)</h3>

    <p>INP replaced First Input Delay in March 2024 and measures responsiveness across all user interactions, not merely the first. JavaScript-heavy sites common among Surrey Research Park technology companies frequently fail INP because of long-running scripts blocking the main thread.</p>

    <p>I address INP through code splitting, deferred script loading, web worker offloading, and reducing the footprint of third-party scripts, the digital equivalent of clearing a cluttered workshop so the craftsperson can actually move.</p>

    <h3>Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)</h3>

    <p>CLS measures visual stability, and elements that shift position during page load frustrate users while signalling poor quality to Google. Common causes include images without dimension attributes, dynamically injected advertising units, and web fonts that trigger layout reflow.</p>

    <p>I eliminate CLS by setting explicit dimensions on all media, reserving space for dynamic content, and implementing font-display strategies that prevent layout shifts entirely.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Crawlability and Indexation</h2>

    <p>If Google cannot find your pages, nothing else matters. Crawlability is the most fundamental technical SEO requirement, and it is where most Guildford business websites harbour undiagnosed problems.</p>

    <h3>Robots.txt and Crawl Directives</h3>

    <p>Your robots.txt file controls which pages search engines can access, and misconfigured directives can inadvertently block entire sections of your site from indexing. I audit robots.txt alongside meta robots tags and X-Robots-Tag headers to ensure consistent, intentional crawl control throughout.</p>

    <h3>XML Sitemaps</h3>

    <p>Sitemaps inform search engines which pages exist and when they were last updated. Effective sitemaps include only indexable, canonical URLs, and I build dynamic sitemaps that automatically exclude noindex pages, redirected URLs, and pagination parameters.</p>

    <h3>Crawl Budget Optimisation</h3>

    <p>Large sites consume crawl budget on low-value pages: faceted navigation, parameter variations, tag archives, and expired content. For Guildford property sites managing thousands of listings, crawl budget optimisation can represent the difference between 30% and 95% of pages being properly indexed.</p>

    <p>I implement crawl budget controls through strategic noindex directives, canonical tags, parameter handling in Google Search Console, and internal link architecture that prioritises high-value pages appropriately.</p>

    <h3>Indexation Monitoring</h3>

    <p>I establish ongoing monitoring through Google Search Console's Index Coverage report, cross-referenced with server log analysis, to identify pages that Google discovers but chooses not to index, the "Crawled - currently not indexed" problem that affects many sites following Core Updates.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="not-prose my-12 py-8 border-y border-border">
      <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Quick enquiry</p>
