    <h2>Structured Data and Schema Markup</h2>

    <p>Structured data helps search engines understand what your pages convey. JSON-LD schema markup can generate rich results in search: star ratings, FAQ dropdowns, event listings, product prices, and business information panels.</p>

    <p>For Guildford local businesses, I implement:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>LocalBusiness schema</strong> with accurate NAP (Name, Address, Phone), opening hours, geo-coordinates, and service area definitions covering Guildford and surrounding Surrey towns.</li>
      <li><strong>Service schema</strong> linking your offerings to your business entity, enabling Google to understand precisely what you provide and where.</li>
      <li><strong>FAQPage schema</strong> that can generate accordion-style results in search, increasing your SERP real estate meaningfully.</li>
      <li><strong>BreadcrumbList schema</strong> that displays your site hierarchy directly within search results.</li>
      <li><strong>Review and AggregateRating schema</strong> for businesses with legitimate customer reviews.</li>
      <li><strong>Event schema</strong> for businesses hosting events at venues like <strong>Guildford Cathedral</strong>, G Live, or the University of Surrey campus.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>All schema is implemented as inline JSON-LD, validated against Google's Rich Results Test, and monitored through Search Console's Enhancements reports on an ongoing basis.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Mobile-First Optimisation</h2>

    <p>Google indexes the mobile version of your site rather than the desktop version, this has been the case since 2023. If your mobile experience is degraded, your rankings reflect that mobile version regardless of how polished your desktop site may appear.</p>

    <p>Mobile-first optimisation for Guildford businesses encompasses:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Responsive design validation</strong> across breakpoints, not merely a cursory check on a single device.</li>
      <li><strong>Touch target sizing</strong> so that buttons and links are comfortably usable on mobile screens without accidental taps.</li>
      <li><strong>Viewport configuration</strong> preventing horizontal scroll and ensuring content fits properly within the screen width.</li>
      <li><strong>Mobile page speed</strong>, which is typically slower than desktop owing to network constraints and less powerful processors.</li>
      <li><strong>Content parity</strong> ensuring that mobile users see the same substantive content as desktop users, including text that may be presented behind accordions or tabs.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Professionals commuting through Guildford station, residents browsing along the <strong>High Street</strong>, and students at the <strong>University of Surrey</strong> are all accessing your site on mobile devices. Your technical infrastructure must serve each of them without friction.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Technical SEO for Surrey Research Park Companies</h2>

    <p>Companies on <strong>Surrey Research Park</strong> present distinct technical SEO challenges that less specialised agencies are apt to overlook. The park's tenant profile skews toward deep-tech, defence, space, and software companies whose websites differ fundamentally from typical SME brochure sites. The <a href="/case-studies/surrey-research-park-tech-startup/">Surrey Research Park tech startup case study</a> covers a comparable JavaScript rendering fix in detail.</p>

    <h3>JavaScript Application Rendering</h3>

    <p>Many Research Park companies build their web presence using the same frontend frameworks they employ in product development: React, Vue, Next.js, and Nuxt. These frameworks can produce sites that are effectively invisible to search engines without proper server-side rendering or static generation.</p>

    <p>I audit rendering behaviour using Google's URL Inspection tool, compare rendered versus raw HTML, and implement rendering strategies that ensure complete indexation without sacrificing the interactive functionality these companies require.</p>

    <h3>International Targeting</h3>

    <p>Satellite communications companies, defence contractors, and scientific instrument manufacturers on the park serve global markets. Hreflang implementation, international URL structures, and geo-targeting configuration require considerable precision, a single hreflang error can cause Google to serve the wrong language version to the wrong market entirely.</p>

    <h3>Security and Compliance</h3>

    <p>Defence-adjacent and healthcare technology companies require HTTPS implementation that goes well beyond a basic SSL certificate. I audit TLS configuration, mixed content issues, and security headers (HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options), ensuring that technical SEO changes do not conflict with existing security requirements.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Technical SEO for Gaming Studios</h2>

    <p>Guildford's gaming cluster, anchored by studios like <strong>Hello Games</strong> and <strong>Media Molecule</strong> alongside numerous independent studios across the town, faces technical SEO challenges driven principally by rich media content and global audiences.</p>

    <h3>Media Asset Optimisation</h3>

    <p>Game studio websites feature trailers, screenshots, concept art, and interactive elements that can push page weight past 10MB without considered intervention. I implement lazy loading, modern image formats, video facade patterns (loading YouTube or Vimeo players only upon interaction), and CDN configuration to deliver media assets from edge servers closest to each user.</p>

    <h3>Launch and Update Page Architecture</h3>

    <p>Game launches generate considerable traffic spikes, and the underlying technical infrastructure must handle sudden load increases without degrading Core Web Vitals. I configure caching strategies, CDN rules, and server scaling that maintain performance during launch windows, precisely when search visibility matters most.</p>

    <h3>Community and Forum Indexation</h3>

    <p>Studios with community forums or user-generated content face index bloat from low-quality pages. I implement pagination controls, canonical strategies for duplicate discussion threads, and noindex rules for user profile pages and empty categories that otherwise dilute crawl budget.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>How I Deliver Technical SEO</h2>

    <p>My technical SEO process follows a structured, methodical approach that ensures nothing is overlooked and every change is properly measured.</p>

    <h3>Phase 1: Technical Audit</h3>

    <p>I crawl your entire site using professional tools, cross-reference findings with Google Search Console data, analyse server logs, and test Core Web Vitals across device types. The output is a prioritised list of issues ranked by their impact on rankings and traffic. My full <a href="/seo-audit-guildford/">SEO audit service</a> provides further detail.</p>

    <h3>Phase 2: Prioritisation and Roadmap</h3>

    <p>Not every technical issue carries equal weight. I categorise findings into critical (blocking indexation or causing ranking loss), high (degrading performance metrics), medium (limiting potential), and low (best practice refinements). You receive a clear roadmap with expected timelines for each phase of work.</p>

    <h3>Phase 3: Implementation</h3>

    <p>I either implement changes directly, where CMS or server access permits, or provide precise specifications for your development team. Every change includes before-and-after validation, and URL changes include comprehensive redirect mapping.</p>

    <h3>Phase 4: Monitoring and Iteration</h3>

    <p>Technical SEO is not a project with a finish line. It is a discipline, more akin to maintaining a garden than building a wall. Google updates its algorithms regularly, CMS patches can introduce quiet regressions, and new content can create unforeseen technical conflicts. Ongoing monitoring catches these problems before they erode your rankings, turning what could be a crisis into a routine correction.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reveal">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    </div>

    <div>
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How long does a technical SEO project take for a Guildford business?</summary>
        <p>Most technical SEO projects run four to twelve weeks depending on site size. A 50-page brochure site for a Guildford professional services firm typically takes four to six weeks, whereas larger sites with thousands of pages, such as property listings or e-commerce catalogues, require eight to twelve weeks for thorough implementation.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the difference between technical SEO and on-page SEO?</summary>
        <p>Technical SEO addresses the infrastructure that search engines rely upon to crawl, render, and index your site. On-page SEO focuses on content quality, keyword targeting, and user intent. Both disciplines are necessary: a technically sound site with poor content will not rank, and excellent content on a compromised site will never be properly indexed.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Do you work with technology companies on Surrey Research Park?</summary>
        <p>I do. I have deep experience with the specific technical requirements of gaming and technology companies on Surrey Research Park, including JavaScript-heavy single-page applications, large media assets, and international audience targeting.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How much does technical SEO cost in Guildford?</summary>
        <p>Technical SEO pricing depends on your site's complexity and current state. A standalone technical audit begins at a fixed fee, and ongoing technical SEO retainers for Guildford businesses are structured on a monthly basis. I would be pleased to discuss a specific quote based on your requirements.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Will technical SEO improvements affect my current rankings?</summary>
        <p>Technical SEO changes are implemented with considerable care to protect existing rankings. I follow a staged approach: audit first, then prioritise fixes by impact and risk. URL changes and redirects are handled with 301 mappings to preserve link equity, and most sites see ranking improvements within four to eight weeks of implementation.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Can you address a Google Core Update ranking decline for my Surrey business?</summary>
        <p>Core Updates are not penalties but rather quality re-evaluations. If your Guildford business lost rankings following a Core Update, a technical audit identifies whether the cause is infrastructure-related (speed, crawlability, rendering) or content-related. I address the technical factors directly and recommend content improvements where appropriate.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is the difference between a 301 and 302 redirect, and why does it matter for SEO?</summary>
        <p>A 301 redirect signals a permanent move and passes ranking value to the new URL, while a 302 redirect signals a temporary move and tells search engines the original URL should stay indexed. Using a 302 for a permanent change can leave ranking signals stuck on the old URL, which is why redirect type matters during migrations, rebrands, or URL restructuring.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What does robots.txt do and can it accidentally block my site from Google?</summary>
        <p>A robots.txt file tells search engine crawlers which pages or directories they should and should not access. A single misconfigured line, such as a blanket Disallow rule left over from a staging environment, can block an entire site from crawling, which is why robots.txt should be checked after every migration or platform change.</p>
      </details>
    </div>

